Here is a simple implementation of a file-based queue system in C# that uses a seek function with a complexity of O(1) to access arbitrary elements in the queue:
```
using System;
using System.IO;

public class FileQueue {
    private readonly string _filePath;
    private long _currentPosition;

    public FileQueue(string filePath) {
        _filePath = filePath;
        _currentPosition = 0;
    }

    // Adds a text line to the queue
    public void Enqueue(string textLine) {
        using (var file = File.AppendText(_filePath)) {
            file.WriteLine(textLine);
        }
    }

    // Removes and returns the next text line in the queue
    public string Dequeue() {
        using (var file = File.OpenText(_filePath)) {
            file.Seek(_currentPosition, SeekOrigin.Begin);
            _currentPosition += file.ReadLine().Length + Environment.NewLine.Length;
            return file.ReadLine();
        }
    }

    // Seek to the next text line in the queue
    public string SeekNext() {
        using (var file = File.OpenText(_filePath)) {
            file.Seek(_currentPosition, SeekOrigin.Begin);
            _currentPosition += file.ReadLine().Length + Environment.NewLine.Length;
            return file.ReadLine();
        }
    }
}
```
This implementation uses a single file to store the text lines in the queue. The `Enqueue` method appends text lines to the end of the file, while the `Dequeue` method reads the next text line from the current position in the file and advances the position to the end of the line. The `SeekNext` method can be used to seek to the next text line in the file, allowing for fast access to arbitrary elements in the queue.

